content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 1
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log errors, warnings and info events, benchmark code and control which events are logged. Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial1 for more details.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 2
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log data that can be graphed and analyzed for min/max/average statistics. Also demonstrates how to use LoggerCircBuf and JTAG Run-Mode to upload events while a target is running . Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial2 for more details.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG RunMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by reading the running target (only works on C64X+ and C66 CPUs). The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 1
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log errors, warnings and info events, benchmark code and control which events are logged. Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial1 for more details.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 2
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log data that can be graphed and analyzed for min/max/average statistics. Also demonstrates how to use LoggerCircBuf and JTAG Run-Mode to upload events while a target is running . Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial2 for more details.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG RunMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by reading the running target (only works on C64X+ and C66 CPUs). The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 1
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log errors, warnings and info events, benchmark code and control which events are logged. Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial1 for more details.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 2
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log data that can be graphed and analyzed for min/max/average statistics. Also demonstrates how to use LoggerCircBuf and JTAG Run-Mode to upload events while a target is running . Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial2 for more details.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG RunMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by reading the running target (only works on C64X+ and C66 CPUs). The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained by reading the running target (only works on C64X+ and C66 CPUs). The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 1
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log errors, warnings and info events, benchmark code and control which events are logged. Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial1 for more details.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 2
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log data that can be graphed and analyzed for min/max/average statistics. Also demonstrates how to use LoggerCircBuf and JTAG Run-Mode to upload events while a target is running . Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial2 for more details.

Also demonstrates how to use LoggerCircBuf and JTAG Run-Mode to upload events while a target is running . Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial2 for more details.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG RunMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by reading the running target (only works on C64X+ and C66 CPUs). The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep JTAG StopMode
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

The Log data is obtained when the target is halted. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: Stairstep ProbePoint
content.desc: The stairstep example runs continuously and periodically generates log events. Different threads (Hwi, Swi, Task) run to present a CPU load to the system. The Log data is obtained by temporarily stopping the target when the Log call is made. The sizes of the loggers in LoggingSetup might need to be decreased if your target does not have enough memory.

content.name: System Analyzer and UIA Tutorial 1
content.desc: This tutorial shows how to log errors, warnings and info events, benchmark code and control which events are logged. Refer to http://processors.wiki.ti.com/index.php/McsaTutorial1 for more details.
